Germany: an expensive budgetary fetish
FRANKFURT – The European Central Bank (ECB) is facing fierce attacks in Germany, a country that for a long time has prided itself on defending the principle of central bank independence.
Moreover, it was Germany that insisted on integrating this principle into the criteria outlined in the Maastricht Treaty, which sets the conditions for membership in the European Monetary Union.
For many members of the Economic and Monetary Union (EMU), the decision to grant independence to their central bank in order to join the eurozone implied a change in political regime.
Thus, the independence of the Banque de France was one of the strongest arguments in the campaign against joining the euro during the 1992 referendum on the ratification of the Maastricht treaty.
In today's Germany, however, it has become, one could say, commonplace to put pressure on the central bank.
For several months, even the Minister of Finance, Wolfgang Schäuble, has regularly commented on the monetary policy of the European Central Bank (ECB).
Schaüble's interventions target the very core of what constitutes the independence of the central bank.
If he does not seek to redefine the objective of monetary policy (this "price norm," in the old Bundesbank jargon), he nonetheless advises on the tools that the ECB should use and how it should handle them to achieve such a goal.
We know of precedents.
In 1998, Oskar Lafontaine, then Minister of Finance of Germany, offered his advice to the first president of the ECB, Wim Duisenberg, on how to conduct monetary policy (Lafontaine's objective was ultimately to create a target zone for exchange rates).
Duisenberg, with his typically Dutch conciseness, replied that it was not incongruous for a politician to express an opinion on monetary policy (in Germany, this was absolutely unusual). "Yet," he added, "it would be entirely abnormal to take [his] suggestions into account."
Sure, please provide the French sentence that you would like translated to English.
The respect for the independence of monetary policy has long been a central element of Germany's Stability Culture ("culture of stability").
The founding act of the Bundesbank's reputation for strict independence was its refusal to yield to Chancellor Konrad Adenauer's exhortations in 1956, when he urged it to curb the rise in interest rates.
At that time, France did not see things in the same way.
Charles de Gaulle was about to create the Fifth Republic, with the Banque de France reporting to the Minister of Finance.
But it was another time.
Following the various crises that have shaken the Eurozone, monetary policy has increasingly tended to replace fiscal policy.
Would the old dogma have become obsolete?
Europe remains highly vulnerable; the median resident of the eurozone has already lost ten years, and what is even more alarming is that we are nearing a critical situation.
However, the United States do better.
Despite a difficult political deadlock to manage, they were able to tackle the macroeconomic problem (the weakness of overall demand) by launching expansionary fiscal and monetary policies.
The United States also handled their banking issues better, which, at first, were much more severe than in Europe.
Of course, there is a strong interaction between the measures that can be taken in both domains.
The more robust an economy is, the more profitable its banks are, and the better they are able to fulfill their function: financing the economy.
But the independence of the ECB is more threatened by the lack of support from the populations than by good advice from a finance minister.
In fact, the famous autonomy of the Bundesbank relied more on the unshakeable support (justified by its performance) of German citizens than on its legal status.
It is exactly the opposite with the ECB.
Voices are being heard, particularly in Germany, calling for increasing the pressure on it.
But the greatest threat to the independence of the ECB lies in the unsustainable burden that weighs on its shoulders.
The less fiscal policy is called upon to stabilize production, the more central banks are in fact constrained to take on this objective (of course, unless they are designed to let nature take its course and allow the economy to get stuck in stagnation, or even worse).
The political result of this sequence is a very clear regression towards nationalism, both right-wing and left-wing, in all UEM countries, including Germany.
The rise of nationalism is almost a logical corollary of the policies pursued.
She is endogenous.
And there too, Germany leads the dance with its obsession with schwarze Null, budget balance, come rain or shine.
In Germany, deficits are viewed negatively not only from an arithmetic perspective but also from a moral one, even though this defies economic common sense and resembles clientelism.
By the end of the 19th century, the main German experts on public finance, including Albert Schäffle and Adolph Wagner, formulated an "golden rule" that current expenditures should be financed, on average, by current revenues.
Public expenditures, and the resources they require, justify themselves through their utility.
This translates to: "Which means that investments aimed at improving productivity – equipment expenses – can be financed with debt, the service of which is guaranteed by the growth of revenues and the base of associated tax receipts."
This classic expense line has been institutionalized in a useful concept: the distinction between current expenses and investment expenses, which is still practiced at the municipal level in Germany (and Austria).
It is crucial because in Germany, about 50% of public sector investment expenditures are managed at this level (with this proportion decreasing, since the municipal share was two-thirds at the beginning of the 1990s).
These expenditures are consistent with support for the competitiveness of German small and medium-sized enterprises (Mittelstand).
But compared to the beginning of the 1990s and in constant prices, investment spending has fallen by about 15%.
Here is more than a decade, and they are insufficient for maintaining the stock of capital.
If this is not how we prepare for the future, then this is how we undermine productivity and prosperity.
In brief, the schwarze Null goes against the intended goal.
The aging infrastructure (though not to the same extent as in the United States) has become a real problem for Germany.
Moreover, the budgetary frugality of German leaders extends beyond German borders, and its effects are amplified by the monetary union, which lacks exchange rates to accommodate national particularisms.
Of course, the European monetary union is imperfect.
But transforming the only institution willing to "do what it takes" to get the Eurozone back on track into a scapegoat is a very bad idea.
The English translation of the given French sentence is:  "Where it exists, allowing states to use the budgetary space they have for relief on the ECB would be a much better strategy."
Germany, without a doubt, enjoys a certain margin of maneuver in this regard.
